:[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Clèves","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (Aberdeenshire): possibly a variant of English   Chevis  . Compare   Cheeves  .","Spanish: variant of   Chevez  .","History: Langdon Cheves (1776–1857), a congressman and financier, was born in Abbeville District, SC. His father was Alexander Chivas, of Buchan, Aberdeenshire, Scotland."],"variants":[{"name":"Cheeves","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Cheves  ."]},{"name":"Chevis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Cecile, Monique.","English (Sussex): from Middle English <i>cheuyn</i>, Old French <i>chevesne</i> ‘chub’, possibly applied as a nickname for someone thought to resemble the fish in some way, or as a metonymic occupational name for a fisherman or fish seller."]}]},{"name":"Mathilde","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."],"variants":[{"name":"Mechtild","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]},{"name":"Matilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]},{"name":"Mechtilde","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mathilde De Clèves was born about 1226, in Luxembourg, Luxembourg, her father, Thierry of cleves lord of dinslaken, was 14 and her mother, Elisabeth van Brabant, was 13. She had at least 3 daughters with Gerard de Limbourg de Luxembourg I."},"et":{"about 1226–":"umbes 1226–Surnud","1226–Female":"1226–Surnud","1236–1283":"1236–1283","1223–1276":"1223–1276","1254–1304":"1254–1304","1255–1328":"1255–1328","1260–1301":"1260–1301","1214–1245":"1214–1245","1214–1272":"1214–1272","19 March 1233":"19. märts 1233","1272":"1272","1283":"1283","1260":"1260","1304":"1304","1226":"1226","1214":"1214","1236":"1236","1301":"1301","1245":"1245","1223":"1223","about 1226":"umbes 1226","1255":"1255","1254":"1254","1276":"1276","1328":"1328","Luxemburg":"Luksemburg","Luxembourg, , , Luxembourg":"Luxembourg, Luksemburg","Leuven, Brabant, Belgium":"Leuven, Brabant, Belgia","Luxembourg, Luxembourg":"Luxembourg, Luksemburg","Europa":"Europe"},"fi":{"about 1226–":"noin 1226–Kuollut","1226–Female":"1226–Kuollut","1236–1283":"1236–1283","1223–1276":"1223–1276","1254–1304":"1254–1304","1255–1328":"1255–1328","1260–1301":"1260–1301","1214–1245":"1214–1245","1214–1272":"1214–1272","19 March 1233":"19. maaliskuuta 1233","1272":"1272","1283":"1283","1260":"1260","1304":"1304","1226":"1226","1214":"1214","1236":"1236","1301":"1301","1245":"1245","1223":"1223","about 122